    <!-- SECTION: Contexts overview -->
    <section class="panel section" style="margin-top:16px;">
      <div class="section-title">Contexts that benefit from a proof layer</div>
      <p class="mini">
        One standard, multiple contexts. Same bundle structure; different lexicon and weighting.
        What changes is not “truth”, but <strong>what must be reconstructible</strong> in that context.
      </p>

      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Regulatory audit window</h3>
          <p class="mini">ISO, internal control, program compliance, training obligations, SOX-like controls, traceability of exceptions.</p>
          <div class="hr"></div>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>definition stability</li>
            <li>data lineage</li>
            <li>quality checks</li>
            <li>repeatability</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h3>Labor / litigation readiness</h3>
          <p class="mini">People decisions contested later: role assignments, promotions, exits, restructurings, sanctions, investigations.</p>
          <div class="hr"></div>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>opposability markers</li>
            <li>chain-of-custody discipline</li>
            <li>what was known when</li>
            <li>who validated what</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h3>Institutional crisis</h3>
          <p class="mini">High-pressure governance: uncertainty logging, escalation timelines, rapid perimeter closure.</p>
          <div class="hr"></div>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>uncertainty log</li>
            <li>escalation trail</li>
            <li>timeline integrity</li>
            <li>blind-spot flags</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="hr"></div>

      <div class="callout">
        <p class="mini" style="margin:0;">
          <strong>CEO rule:</strong> you don’t need 30 pages of narrative.
          You need a bundle that proves: <em>what data existed, what constraints applied, what decision happened, and that nothing was altered afterward.</em>
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION: Boundaries -->
    <section class="panel section">
      <div class="section-title">Data, trust and governance boundaries</div>

      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>What OpenProof does</h3>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>Seals a decision context into a deterministic JSON bundle.</li>
            <li>Produces a readable preview (human mirror of the narrative).</li>
            <li>Computes a public hash (tamper-evident immutability anchor).</li>
            <li>Enables later verification across systems and jurisdictions.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h3>What it does NOT do</h3>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>Does not decide or replace governance.</li>
            <li>Does not expose confidential content publicly.</li>
            <li>Does not “predict truth” or automate judgment.</li>
            <li>Does not require AI to be valuable.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION: Integration perimeter -->
    <section class="panel section">
      <div class="section-title">Integration perimeter (defence-grade reality)</div>
      <p class="mini">
        The proof layer sits <strong>on top</strong> of existing systems. It does not replace them.
        It captures “what the organization relied on” at the time of decision.
      </p>

      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Typical sources</h3>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>HRIS / HCM (Workforce, org, job, comp)</li>
            <li>LMS / compliance training</li>
            <li>Security / IT logs (high-level markers)</li>
            <li>Legal snapshots / policies / constraints</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Bundle contains</h3>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>Issuer / subject, timestamp (ISO-8601)</li>
            <li>Narrative + human-readable preview hash</li>
            <li>Evidence registry (IDs, descriptors, hashes)</li>
            <li>Public hash (deterministic validation)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>CEO outcomes</h3>
          <ul class="bullets">
            <li>Audit-ready decision replay</li>
            <li>Lower “unknowns” in crisis</li>
            <li>Clear accountability boundaries</li>
            <li>Less narrative warfare, more structure</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

